<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920212-0071</DOCNO><DOCID>920212-0071.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Data Translation Inc.:   Firm Wins Verdict in Suit   Over Federal Contract Talks</HL><DATE>02/12/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   DATX</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><NS>GOVERNMENT CONTRACTS (GVC)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Jurors in a federal court in Boston decided in favor ofData Translation Inc. in a suit alleging that the companywithheld pricing data in negotiating federal contracts.   The complaint, filed by the U.S. attorney's office in1989, involved negotiations between Data Translation and theGeneral Service Administration over the sale of automaticdata processing equipment to federal agencies. It allegedthat Data Translation provided false and incompleteinformation about its sales and discount practices in 1983,when the contract was negotiated, and in 1984, when it wasrenewed.</LP><TEXT>   In the suit, the government asked that Data Translation beliable for treble damages of $1,318,242, and penalties of asmuch as $10,000 for each of at least 214 invoices submittedby the company. The government charged that contractsobtained by the company, a maker of computer products basedin Marlboro, Mass., were inflated by $439,414.   &quot;The company contended throughout that it had disclosedall required information,&quot; said Ellen Harpin, a spokeswomanfor Data Translation. The U.S. attorney's office, which has60 days to appeal Monday's verdict, had no comment.</TEXT></DOC>